http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/letters/Economic-slowdown/article14012159.ece

The lower global economic growth forecast by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) for 2016 confirms that across the world, economies are passing through the most trying times since the 2008 financial crisis (“Dealing with the slowdown”, Jan.21). The present meltdown has been triggered mainly by the slump experienced by the Chinese economy and an unabated fall in crude oil prices. That the IMF has kept the growth rate projection for India unchanged at 7.5 per cent could make India a sweet spot for investment. The troubles in China could be a boon in disguise. The rollout of laws like the Goods and Services Tax (GST) will further improve ease of doing business. The coming budget presents an attractive opportunity.Philip Sabu,Thrissur